<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence from Surrey County Council (LTD0016)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Written evidence from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Surrey County Council</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (LTD0016)</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the rationale for the Government’s proposals to devolve to a local level </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">decision-making on transport expenditure? What are the advantages and disadvantages of the Government’s approach? Are there better models</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The benefits of local decision-making include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">peed of delivery - it removes a layer of bureaucracy if we do not hav</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e to seek </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment approval.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ore tailored to local needs. Residents, businesses and local authorities know where most of the problems are. They know which transport networks have insufficient capacity and where congestion most commonly happens.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The disa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">dvantages include:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">llocating all funds to the local level removes (or reduces) the capacity to fund larger schemes. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he need to compete for funds for smaller major schemes </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">costing </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">between £2</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> million and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">£5 million is time-consuming and adds uncertainty. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Better models:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">onsistency of approach instead of changing the system every few years</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ewer competitions</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">More money (revenue and capital) spent on infrastructure development and delivery and less on red tape.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do local bodies (including local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">authorities, local enterprise partnerships, passenger transport executives, integrated transport authorities and local transport boards) have the capacity to assess, prioritise and deliver local transport schemes? What would the optimum delivery body look </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">like?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The capacity to deliver local transport schemes varies considerably from authority to authority.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most will struggle to deliver enough schemes at the higher levels of funding possible under the new local growth deals. Local authorities are being force</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d to reduce the size of their teams because of overall reductions in levels of funding in particular revenue.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">We can increase capacity, but we need time and revenue funding to do this. We also need reassurance that any extra capacity we do acquire will not</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> be wasted if the Government changes its mind about levels of funding. A successful approach would commit capital and revenue funding over a 15 to 20 year period which is the gestation period for the larger major schemes.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The optimum client delivery body w</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ould have sufficient technical capacity to ensure value for money through feasibility and modelling.  It should be able to deliver transport improvements quickly and flexibly.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What is the best way of dealing with major transport schemes that cross local </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">authority boundaries or have wider regional impact?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">There are two methods:</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:5pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">First, the Government could hold a fund at the national level for schemes like these.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; margin:0pt 0pt 5pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Secondly, local authorities and LEPs could pool their resources to pay for a scheme of joint im</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">portance.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How effectively do local bodies work with each other and with </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">overnment departments and national transport agencies?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">On the whole, there are good working relationships between different local bodies. The biggest problem is the interface between </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">local and national. All too often, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Government introduces new initiatives and changes its approaches too quickly.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Do the current funding streams for major local transport schemes meet the needs of local authorities? How do current funding streams compar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">e with previous arrangements?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Too bureaucratic. We spent a long time creating local transport bodies only for these to be mostly superseded by growth deals. We don’t yet know how the new arrangements will work.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The old arrangements also had their problems including slow decision-making by </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">It did not make sense that the Hindhead </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">unnel had to be funded from the old regional pot. It was much too expensive (£371 million) and strategically important to be</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> suitable for regional funding. Should have been a national scheme.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Most LEPs will struggle to get agreement to pool funds for worthy schemes above £100</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> million </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">particularly when local authorities find that other smaller improvements with benefits are esse</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ntially shelved for many years.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In order to ensure delivery post 2015 LEPs should be advised to allocate revenue funding to promoters with approved programmed schemes to develop robust business cases.  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">What impact will the devolution in 2015 of funding to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> Local Transport Bodies and the introduction of the Single Local Growth Fund have?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">A huge amount of extra work for everyone. A list of deliverable schemes needs to be developed following many years when limited funding was available for schemes development</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Huge pressure on revenue budgets to develop the schemes at a time when </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ocal </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">uthorities are facing budget pressures and staff cuts from an already low staff position.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Unrealistic expectations from </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">g</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">overnment about the amount of local contributions that </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are possible.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How can local authorities attract greater investment from the private sector for the delivery and maintenance of local transport infrastructure? What scope is there for the use of alternative funding streams?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The challenge is to find a mecha</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nism which will give a financial return. The private sector will occasionally fund transport infrastructure that has a direct bearing on their business - eg </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the A3 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">hospital roundabout</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in Guildford</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. But it is a lot harder to attract funding for more general</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> infrastructure - eg a strategic junction.</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Alternative funding streams such as section 106/ CIL are possible, but there are many calls on them (</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such as the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">rising need for more school places).  </span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">How clear are the lines of accountability for local decision </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">making on transport expenditure?</span></p><p style="margin:5pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">At the moment, not very! We do not know how the new growth fund governance arrangements will work, or how they will relate to local transport bodies.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">December 2013</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>